pr_review_comment_body:
@kbandla The [coveralls report for dns.py](https://coveralls.io/builds/8578836/source?filename=dpkt%2Fdns.py) isn't quite working: 

> The owner of this repo needs to re-authorize with github; their OAuth credentials are no longer valid so the file cannot be pulled from the github API.

Anyways, I looked at a local coverage report and that proved the `RR` class `pack` and `unpack`  methods are only tested in the common case.

@markrwilliams  I don't think we want seek and read to act on bytes (that's really what EncodedFile actually buys). If you drop out that, then seek and read don't work the way they do on StringIO and that prevents this from being a useful drop in replacement. I don't know exactly how to make tell() not provide info about what byte you're on (and maybe it shouldn't).

Really though I think in retrospect, len on SpooledStringIO should report the number of codepoints and not the number of bytes (otherwise again we're off of the StringIO api). One of the reasons that these classes are useful is that they provide a consistent API for different kinds of file and file-like objects. 

I have an idea for making len work as expected. I'll think about tell a bit more.

